(130, '0', ' Check out foods that are cheaper in Ghana but expensive in other countries', '', 'lifestyle', '<p>The cost of food can vary significantly from one country to another due to several factors, such as availability, production costs, and import/export taxes. In the case of Ghana, there are certain types of food that are relatively cheap compared to other countries. This affordability can be attributed to local production, favorable climatic conditions, and cultural preferences. Here are some examples of food items that are inexpensive in Ghana but expensive in other countries:</p><p><br></p><p>1. Plantains: Plantains are a staple food in Ghana and are readily available at low prices. Due to favorable growing conditions, plantains are abundant, making them affordable for the local population. However, in other countries where plantains are not commonly grown, they need to be imported, which significantly increases their price.</p><p><br></p><p>2. Cassava: Cassava, a root vegetable, is widely consumed in Ghana. It is not only a low-cost food but also a versatile ingredient used in various dishes. The abundance of cassava in Ghana makes it accessible to the majority of the population. In contrast, in other countries where cassava is not as common, it needs to be imported, which drives up its cost.</p><p><br></p><p>3. Local fruits: Ghana is known for its diverse range of fruits, including mangoes, pineapples, papayas, and bananas. These fruits are grown locally and are typically sold at affordable prices. However, in other countries where these fruits are imported, transportation costs and import duties contribute to their higher prices.</p><p><br></p><p>4. Fresh fish: Ghana has a long coastline, providing access to a rich variety of fish. As a result, fresh fish is relatively inexpensive compared to landlocked countries or regions where fish needs to be transported over long distances.</p><p><br></p><p>5. Local grains: Grains such as maize, millet, and sorghum are commonly consumed in Ghana and are often sold at reasonable prices. These grains are locally produced and have a lower cost of production compared to imported grains in other countries.</p><p><br></p><p>It is important to note that while these food items may be cheap in Ghana, their prices can still vary depending on factors such as location, seasonality, and market demand. Additionally, the cost of living and individual purchasing power also play a role in determining affordability. Nonetheless, the aforementioned food items generally tend to be less expensive in Ghana compared to other countries.</p><div><br></div>', 'best-Ghanaian-Food.jpg', '', '', 'source ', '  14th  September 2023', 1);
