(205, '0', ' What is a slow drain? Here is what you need to know about slow drian and 6 Ways to Deal with it', '-What-is-a-slow-drain-Here-is-what-you-need-to-know-about-slow-drian-and-6-Ways-to-Deal-with-it', 'plumbing', '<p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"0aab4807-f14e-44f2-b18d-62eded605c5b\" data-pm-slice=\"1 1 []\"><strong><wt-ignore uuid=\"e25c50a0-b6bc-4d78-96ea-6f0c6bdd0254\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">What</wt-ignore> is a slow <wt-ignore uuid=\"cc22df16-5b00-4b77-89f7-50aeee40d2a4\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">drain?</wt-ignore></strong></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"2f0acded-7d85-43d6-b687-c4586d872ca4\"> <span class=\"issue-underline underline decoration-2 underline-offset-4 transition decoration-border-brand-default [.long-form-editing-active_&amp;]:decoration-border-brand-default/50 hover:bg-bg-brand-light-default\" data-issueid=\"d2a25d73-0538-4163-96e8-b245671f6838\" aria-label=\"open issue for the following text A slow drain is\" data-testid=\"issue-underline:undefined\">A slow drain is</span> when a sink, tub, or toilet takes an unusually long time to drain. It is caused <span class=\"issue-underline underline decoration-2 underline-offset-4 transition decoration-border-brand-default [.long-form-editing-active_&amp;]:decoration-border-brand-default/50 hover:bg-bg-brand-light-default\" data-issueid=\"3ffcb677-07e6-4520-8ce2-ed6e4a40cca0\" aria-label=\"open issue for the following text by a buildup of soap, hair, and other debris in\" data-testid=\"issue-underline:undefined\">by a buildup of soap, hair, and other debris in</span> pipes. There are <span class=\"issue-underline underline decoration-2 underline-offset-4 transition decoration-border-brand-default [.long-form-editing-active_&amp;]:decoration-border-brand-default/50 hover:bg-bg-brand-light-default\" data-issueid=\"62a7af2a-f051-4652-9a22-475522d13b63\" aria-label=\"open issue for the following text a variety of\" data-testid=\"issue-underline:undefined\">a variety of</span> ways to clear a slow drain, such as <wt-ignore uuid=\"fde0c335-c14c-46c1-8cd4-186cc870cc20\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">using:</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"4477bebf-0ddd-4252-a62c-f7109968a073\"><strong>1. Use a Plunger:</strong><wt-ignore uuid=\"e09ee787-3b86-4b1f-b2fe-63c9754892f9\" source=\"wt-feature-result\"> One of the most effective ways to deal with slow drains is by using a plunger. Place the plunger over the drain and vigorously plunge up and down several times to create suction. This can help dislodge any clogs and improve drainage.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"1d2a4ab7-bb8d-402f-a7b0-0a2dd8d214e8\"><strong>2. Boiling Water:</strong><wt-ignore uuid=\"e09ee787-3b86-4b1f-b2fe-63c9754892f9\" source=\"wt-feature-result\"> Another simple and cost-effective solution is to pour boiling water down the drain. This can help dissolve grease, soap scum, and other debris that may be causing the blockage. Be cautious when handling boiling water and avoid using this method on plastic pipes.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"d450e2a1-ee19-4112-9dd7-6bd7389d191e\"><strong>3. Baking Soda and Vinegar:</strong><wt-ignore uuid=\"e09ee787-3b86-4b1f-b2fe-63c9754892f9\" source=\"wt-feature-result\"> Create a natural drain cleaner by combining baking soda and vinegar. Start by pouring half a cup of baking soda down the drain, followed by half a cup of vinegar. Let the mixture sit for about 30 minutes, then flush it with hot water. The chemical reaction between baking soda and vinegar can help break down clogs and eliminate odors.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"93f680a1-6413-4d21-aaea-bac9f43a2cc9\"><strong>4. Chemical Drain Cleaners:</strong><wt-ignore uuid=\"e09ee787-3b86-4b1f-b2fe-63c9754892f9\" source=\"wt-feature-result\"> If the above methods don\'t work, you may consider using a chemical drain cleaner. These products contain powerful chemicals that can dissolve stubborn clogs. However, they should be used with caution and following the manufacturer\'s instructions, as they can be harmful to your health and the environment.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"dd8ebce0-0a8b-4960-9aad-477dd278ac1e\"><strong>5. Plumbing Snake:</strong><wt-ignore uuid=\"e09ee787-3b86-4b1f-b2fe-63c9754892f9\" source=\"wt-feature-result\"> A plumbing snake, also known as an auger, is a tool that can be used to remove clogs from drains. Insert the snake into the drain and rotate it clockwise to dislodge any blockages. Slowly pull out the snake, and the clog should come out with it.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"891b54af-eea6-48c3-a5db-75d6dac11fcf\"><strong>6. Call a Professional:</strong><wt-ignore uuid=\"e09ee787-3b86-4b1f-b2fe-63c9754892f9\" source=\"wt-feature-result\"> If none of the above methods work or if you\'re not comfortable dealing with the issue yourself, it\'s best to call a professional plumber. They have the expertise and tools necessary to diagnose and fix the underlying cause of the slow drain. Hiring a professional can save you time, money, and potential damage to your plumbing system.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"4fb6b0a8-60e8-4b0c-92a1-fb33e259aadf\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"e09ee787-3b86-4b1f-b2fe-63c9754892f9\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">By following these six methods, you can effectively deal with slow drains and ensure proper drainage in your home. Remember to always practice preventive measures, such as avoiding pouring grease and hair down the drain, to minimize the occurrence of clogs in the future.</wt-ignore></p>', 'iStock-1359885340.jpg', '', '', 'source ', '  27th  September 2023', 1),
(206, '0', 'How to Fix Cracked Glass', 'How-to-Fix-Cracked-Glass', 'mechanical', '<p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"7905a14b-2ec5-405b-acc5-847a75edf739\" data-pm-slice=\"1 1 []\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">Introduction:</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"bb6c0a5e-689b-48c7-86fe-e5cf6335dbf6\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">Cracked glass can be a frustrating problem, but fortunately, it is possible to repair it. In this guide, we will explain step-by-step how to fix cracked glass, providing you with a cost-effective solution to restore its functionality and appearance.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"971ec66b-0b76-4b51-82b1-be4d03d40280\"><strong>Materials Needed:</strong></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"8a944b5b-9e8c-4ef8-a004-f00b80a9fe04\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">Before getting started, gather the following materials:</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"adf2d0b4-1660-4d5d-932c-bdd281ef72bf\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">1. Safety gloves</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"2295400d-961c-48c1-9bf5-df6ec902bb33\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">2. Safety goggles</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"d5d56d5b-2de2-4696-80aa-84cc9fa83c7a\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">3. Glass cleaner</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"0cf52488-01bd-4e3a-94ee-e50d2767c707\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">4. Razor blade or glass cutter</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"86a391aa-0baf-4446-9500-2e0382886e24\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">5. Clear adhesive or glass glue</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"61300ec9-a515-4e80-af5b-ebd4e4a02088\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">6. Clamps or heavy objects</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"a7be4ae6-d90d-4453-accd-da69193219ed\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">7. Fine-grit sandpaper</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"fee6e427-e1f3-4a1e-bd01-2c83faefa66c\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">8. Paintbrush</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"bcea15e5-a347-4465-a9f6-549be74908cf\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">9. Glass repair kit (optional)</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"d0f182f8-8b59-4fa3-aa42-ff0f21fe4939\"><strong>Step 1: Safety Precautions</strong></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"968a83fe-1b51-45e2-a824-448a2efa4b54\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">Before attempting any repairs, it is crucial to prioritize safety. Put on safety gloves to protect your hands from sharp edges, and wear safety goggles to shield your eyes from any glass fragments during the repair process.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"ceff4c0e-b0ae-42ba-a5ca-269e3b631a9f\"><strong>Step 2: Clean the Glass</strong></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"6fdd40e6-63ed-4f71-bd8d-bf8c29de4f6d\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">Thoroughly clean the cracked glass using a glass cleaner to remove any dirt or debris. This will ensure proper adhesion when applying the adhesive later on.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"b79120a0-767e-4478-9262-9f95c8860ff0\"><strong>Step 3: Assess the Damage</strong></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"52f8f8a6-6dc0-4e31-89a5-e7bf102289c2\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">Examine the cracked glass to determine the extent of the damage. If the crack is minor, you may be able to proceed with a simple repair. However, if the crack is severe or the glass is shattered, it may be necessary to replace the entire piece.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"6bfe063b-3004-48c4-9efc-a74d921a68e9\"><strong>Step 4: Stabilize the Crack</strong></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"5d6cc539-dc49-4f79-a642-bdb4940d370d\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">To prevent further spreading, stabilize the crack by making small holes at each end using a razor blade or glass cutter. This will relieve stress on the glass and help prevent the crack from getting worse.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"0b3d006b-7ab7-4032-827a-176c100e7043\"><strong>Step 5: Apply Adhesive</strong></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"5703314f-c37a-4d9a-86be-8336c593039d\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">Using a clear adhesive or glass glue, carefully apply a small amount along the crack. Use a paintbrush to spread the adhesive evenly, ensuring it fills the crack completely. Be careful not to use too much adhesive, as it may overflow when pressure is applied.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"a2236e0e-23ab-4412-9dae-066690db5a62\"><strong>Step 6: Apply Pressure</strong></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"ac088d9c-b45c-46d8-af5e-5f37a57fb06f\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">Gently press the cracked glass together, aligning the edges as closely as possible. If the crack is on a flat surface, place clamps or heavy objects on top to apply even pressure. Leave the adhesive to dry according to the manufacturer\'s instructions.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"f6b77cf6-482f-4c05-ac19-041d44ee5331\"><strong>Step 7: Sand and Finish (Optional)</strong></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"9aa64a94-7141-4b12-868f-d1d54fb707ed\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">If desired, once the adhesive has fully dried, use fine-grit sandpaper to smooth out any rough edges or excess adhesive. This step is particularly useful for aesthetic purposes, ensuring the repaired glass appears seamless.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"e3f8b21d-afaa-4433-be35-47026229b397\"><strong>Step 8: Monitor and Maintain</strong></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"e01bd5b6-1fb1-4d33-beaa-8493d0210c88\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">After repairing the cracked glass, it\'s important to monitor it for any signs of further damage. Avoid subjecting the glass to excessive stress or impact, as this may cause the crack to reappear or worsen. Regularly clean and maintain the glass to prolong its lifespan.</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"1bde293a-c99c-40c3-88a0-8e4629dd4ad5\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">Conclusion:</wt-ignore></p><p data-private=\"redact\" class=\"pb-2\" data-wt-guid=\"207f7c08-4eff-4141-980c-24b9068cb486\"><wt-ignore uuid=\"ae805e9f-5253-4506-afb8-585245b5cc2a\" source=\"wt-feature-result\">Fixing cracked glass is a feasible task that can save you the cost of replacing the entire piece. By following these step-by-step instructions, you can repair minor cracks and restore the functionality and appearance of your glass. Remember to prioritize safety throughout the process and monitor the repaired glass for any signs of further damage.</wt-ignore></p>', 'iStock-614347236.jpg', '', '', 'source ', '  27th  September 2023', 1),
